So what is Leukaemia? #Leukaemia is cancer that starts in the tissue that forms blood.
In a person with #leukaemia, the bone marrow makes abnormal white blood cells. The abnormal cells are leukaemia cells.
Unlike normal blood cells, #leukaemia cells do not die when they should.
#Leukaemia cells crowd out normal white blood cells,red blood cells,and platelets.This makes it hard for normal blood cells to do their work
Chronic Lymphocytic #Leukaemia affects lymphoid cells and usually grows slowly.Most often,people diagnosed with the disease are over age 55
Chronic myeloid #leukaemia (CML): CML affects myeloid cells and usually grows slowly at first. It mainly affects adults.
Chronic myeloid #leukaemia (CML): CML affects myeloid cells and usually grows slowly at first. It mainly affects adults.
Acute lymphocytic (lymphoblastic) #leukaemia affects lymphoid cells and grows quickly.
Acute myeloid #leukaemia (AML): AML affects myeloid cells and grows quickly. It occurs in both adults and children.
Risk: Exposed to very high levels of radiation (Atomic bomb explosions, Radiation therapy, Diagnostic x-rays) #leukaemia
Smoking cigarettes increases the risk of acute myeloid #leukaemia.
Exposure to benzene in the workplace can cause acute myeloid #leukaemia.
Down syndrome and certain other inherited diseases increase the risk of developing acute #leukaemia.
Look out for swollen lymph nodes that usually do not hurt (especially lymph nodes in the neck or armpit) #Leukaemia

3 crucial checks for #leukaemia
1. Physical exam
2. Blood Test
3. Biopsy

Physical exam: The doctor checks for swollen lymph
nodes, spleen, or liver. #leukaemia.

Blood tests: The lab does a complete blood count to
check the number of white blood cells, red blood cells,
and platelets. #leukaemia.
#Leukaemia causes a very high level of white blood cells
Biopsy: The doctor removes tissue to look for cancer cells. #Leukaemia
